ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `bzfgrep` command works like `grep`, but is specifically designed to search within `bzip2` compressed files. This means you don't need to manually unzip the file; `bzfgrep` handles the decompression and searching process automatically.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `bzfgrep "text" file.bz2` --> Searches for "text" within the `file.bz2`.
    ðŸ”¹ `bzfgrep -i "text" file.bz2` -->  Performs a case-insensitive search for "text" in `file.bz2`.
    ðŸ”¹ `bzfgrep -c "text" file.bz2` --> Only displays the count of lines where "text" is found.
    ðŸ”¹ `bzfgrep -l "text" *.bz2` --> Lists the names of files where "text" is found.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ bzfgrep "error" logfile.bz2

    ðŸ”¹ Finds lines containing the word "error" in `logfile.bz2`.

    $ bzfgrep -i "warning" logfile.bz2

    ðŸ”¹ Finds lines containing the word "warning" or "WARNING" (case-insensitive) in `logfile.bz2`.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

    $ bzfgrep -c "2023-10-26" access.log.bz2

